, it's always going to come back to, you know, you have to make those deliveries as, as requested.

00:13:39.619 --> 00:13:44.659
But when you're building the infrastructure in a way that makes that delivery, let's say

00:13:44.659 --> 00:13:50.099
reproducible or makes that infrastructure reproducible. And then, and they see the

00:13:50.099 --> 00:13:55.219
speed at which you can turn things around in the future. Because inevitably,

00:13:55.219 --> 00:13:59.619
we all probably experienced this. Someone's going to ask a question or want a delivery.

00:13:59.619 --> 00:14:06.020
And then they want some variant of that delivery three months from now, right? And so you go build,

00:14:06.099 --> 00:14:10.820
you build that first iteration, maybe it takes you, you know, a week longer to do it.

00:14:11.460 --> 00:14:15.539
But if you do it right, the next time they come around, it turns around a day,

00:14:16.179 --> 00:14:20.260
they they fall out of their chairs, right? And I think that that's where all of a sudden,

00:14:20.900 --> 00:14:25.859
you're you're showing that, look, this is this is the value of doing things in a manner that's

00:14:25.859 --> 00:14:31.780
that's reproducible and scalable, because we're saving costs, where we are turning things around

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:37.700
that impresses, you know, the customer. And, you know, and those are the things where you're like,

00:14:37.700 --> 00:14:44.500
okay, you know, regardless of who's doing it, that the operation of the data program is,

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:51.700
is, is efficient, right? And so I take I take pride in that I love kind of efficiency in that regard.

