it's easy, just what Seth was saying, it's not easy, but it's easier when there's a very small

01:05:08.100 --> 01:05:12.899
group, because you can have that one-to-one dialogue that says, okay, I know what you're

01:05:12.899 --> 01:05:17.300
doing. You know what I'm doing. We know the tools that we have. Let's come together and get this

01:05:17.300 --> 01:05:22.659
done. When you go to a really big organization, and this comes back to something that Frank was

01:05:22.659 --> 01:05:29.139
saying, there's a tendency for people to grab the tools they know, hack it, whatever they need to do

01:05:29.219 --> 01:05:34.500
to get today's work done and get it out the door. And the problem there is that in doing that

01:05:34.500 --> 01:05:39.620
process, they leave a damn mess everywhere. You know, they leave the pots and pans lying about

01:05:39.620 --> 01:05:45.860
and everything's, you know, messy and they don't clean up afterwards. And so, you know, having,

01:05:45.860 --> 01:05:53.459
as the organization grows, having people that know what they're doing, you know, know exactly

01:05:53.459 --> 01:05:59.540
what's expected to get what they need to do, do what they need to do, and then leave the place in

01:05:59.540 --> 01:06:04.419
a tidy framework, because they know that they're going to have to do it again, you know, in a

01:06:04.419 --> 01:06:11.860
minute or in an hour or tomorrow. And so there's that kind of chef-y thing of mise en place. You

01:06:11.860 --> 01:06:16.659
chop up, you get all the pieces nice and tidy so that when the orders start coming in thick and

01:06:16.659 --> 01:06:25.860
fast, you know you can get your job done. And my, you know, I work in a big organization and,

01:06:26.580 --> 01:06:30.979
you know, there's an awful lot of people who are doing their own way, you know, and I kind

01:06:30.979 --> 01:06:36.260
of like the tidyverse thing of it's opinionated, but it's opinionated for a reason because you can

01:06:36.260 --> 01:06:42.500
then, you know, reproduce that pipeline again and again and again using the same kind of tools.

01:06:43.459 --> 01:06:47.699
You know, I have lots of colleagues that learned R 10 years ago and they're all base R and they're

01:06:47.699 --> 01:06:52.500
like, yeah, but I can do that in base R. It's like, that's great. I'm really happy for you that you can

01:06:52.500 --> 01:06:58.419
do that in base R. This isn't a competition. This isn't code golf. You know, I'd like us to

01:06:58.419 --> 01:07:02.580
be able to do it in a way that I can pass my stuff to you, you can pass your stuff to me,

01:07:03.780 --> 01:07:09.219
and, you know, we know what we're going to get and we can then be part of that, you know, chain of

01:07:09.300 --> 01:07:14.979
getting stuff out the door, but getting it out the door, looking good, smart, fulfilling the brief,

01:07:16.419 --> 01:07:20.820
you know, what everyone wants to see on their plate. I'm sorry, I'm all about analogies.

01:07:22.340 --> 01:07:29.060
I love it. You're inspiring me to go get better organized.

